<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ870716-0138 </DOCNO><HL> International Corporate Report</HL><DD> 07/16/87</DD><SO> WALL STREET JOURNAL (J)</SO><IN> EUROPEARNINGS (ERN)ELECTRIC, ELECTRONICS, APPLIANCES (ELE)TEXTILES AND APPAREL (TEX) </IN><TEXT>   SHARP CORP., a major Japanese electronics company, said consolidated earnings in the year ended March 31 plunged 42% from the previous year, to 20.78 billion yen ($137.5 million) from 35.94 billion yen. Sales fell 5.5%, to 1.149 trillion yen ($7.6 billion) from 1.216 trillion yen. Overseas sales fell below domestic sales for the first time in eight years, because of the yen's sharp appreciation, company officials said.    The European Community Commission decided that BOUSSAC SAINT-FRERES S.A., the French textiles concern, must repay 338 million French francs ($54.9 million) it received from the French government in violation of EC competition rules. The commission gave its decision after months of talks with Boussac's current owner, the French holding company SOCIETE FINANCIERE AGACHE S.A., and the French Finance Ministry.    DIXONS GROUP PLC, a major British electrical-appliance retailer, said pre-tax profit rose 31% in the year ended May 2, to #102.6 million ($165.3 million) from #78.1 million the year before. Net income nearly doubled, to #77.6 million from 38.7 million. Sales climbed 18%, to #1.11 billion ($1.79 billion) from #943.4 million. </TEXT></DOC>